{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1313"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.02,0.02,0.75,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1313"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of recurrent palpitations. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left ventricular hypertrophy","Atrial fibrillation","Sinus tachycardia","Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome","Supraventricular tachycardia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shows a narrow-complex regular rhythm at just over 80 beats per minute. Significant findings include left axis deviation, dominant R-wave in V1, \u0027delta\u0027 wave, and a shortened PR interval. The left axis deviation is indicated by the positive QRS complex in lead I and negative QRS complex in lead aVF. The dominant R-wave is observed in lead V1, which is atypical and suggests pre-excitation. The \u0027delta\u0027 wave, a slurred upstroke of the QRS complex, is visible in multiple leads, and the PR interval is shortened to less than 120 ms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWolff-Parkinson-White syndrome (WPW)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. WPW is caused by the presence of a congenital accessory pathway, leading to pre-excitation of the ventricles. This results in the characteristic ECG findings of a shortened PR interval (\u0026lt;120 ms) and a delta wave (slurred upstroke of the QRS complex), both of which are present in this ECG. The dominant R wave and left axis deviation suggest a type A pattern of WPW. The palpitations could represent periods of tachycardia resulting from the aberrant pathway. Treatment is ablation of the aberrant pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the ECG does not meet the voltage criteria for LVH, and it doesn\u0027t explain the shortened PR interval or delta wave.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E is ruled out as the rhythm is regular with clearly visible P waves and no fibrillatory waves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESinus tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the heart rate is not elevated enough to be classified as tachycardia, and it doesn\u0027t explain the abnormal ECG findings such as the shortened PR interval and delta wave.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupraventricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E (SVT). The patient does not have SVT as he is currently not tachycardic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients presenting with WPW, further evaluation is necessary to assess the risk of sudden cardiac death. Management options may include antiarrhythmic medications or catheter ablation of the accessory pathway, depending on the patient\u0027s symptoms and risk assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Shortened PR interval and delta wave are characteristic ECG findings of Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome.","Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome is caused by a congenital accessory pathway leading to pre-excitation of the ventricles.","AV nodal blocking agents should be avoided in Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome due to the risk of precipitating ventricular tachycardia/fibrillation."],"references":["Chhabra L, Goyal A, Benham MD. Wolff Parkinson White Syndrome [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554437/","Brugada J, Katritsis DG, Arbelo E, Arribas F, Bax JJ, Blomstr\u00f6m-Lundqvist C, et al. 2019 ESC Guidelines for the management of patients with supraventricular tachycardiaThe Task Force for the management of patients with supraventricular tachycardia of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC). Eur Heart J. 2020 Feb 1;41(5):655-720. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31504425/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20434"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20434"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Vs3ySpEKlgxYpZ1IS5JP9XvwjSjf5V.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Vs3ySpEKlgxYpZ1IS5JP9XvwjSjf5V.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":323}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-20T17:31:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-20T19:37:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1313"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta